# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: algebraic-combinatorics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/algebraic-combinatorics] The term "algebraic combinatorics" was introduced in the late 1970s.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/algebraic-combinatorics] This period is reflected in the area 05E, *Algebraic combinatorics*, of the AMS Mathematics Subject Classification, introduced in 1991.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/algebraic-combinatorics] Algebraic combinatorics has come to be seen more expansively as an area of mathematics where the interaction of combinatorial and algebraic methods is particularly strong and significant.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/algebraic-combinatorics] Thus the combinatorial topics may be enumerative in nature or involve matroids, polytopes, partially ordered sets, or finite geometries.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/algebraic-combinatorics] On the algebraic side, besides group theory and representation theory, lattice theory and commutative algebra are commonly used.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/algebraic-combinatorics] The ring of symmetric functions is a specific limit of the rings of symmetric polynomials in *n* indeterminates, as *n* goes to infinity.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/algebraic-combinatorics] This ring serves as universal structure in which relations between symmetric polynomials can be expressed in a way independent of the number *n* of indeterminates (but its elements are neither polynomials nor functions).
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/algebraic-combinatorics] Among other things, this ring plays an important role in the representation theory of the symmetric groups.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/algebraic-combinatorics] An association scheme is a collection of binary relations satisfying certain compatibility conditions.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/algebraic-combinatorics] Association schemes provide a unified approach to many topics, for example combinatorial designs and coding theory.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/algebraic-combinatorics] In algebra, association schemes generalize groups, and the theory of association schemes generalizes the character theory of linear representations of groups.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/algebraic-combinatorics] A strongly regular graph is defined as follows.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/algebraic-combinatorics] Let *G* = (*V*,*E*) be a regular graph with *v* vertices and degree *k*.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/algebraic-combinatorics] A graph of this kind is sometimes said to be a srg(*v*, *k*, λ, μ).
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/algebraic-combinatorics] Some authors exclude graphs which satisfy the definition trivially, namely those graphs which are the disjoint union of one or more equal-sized complete graphs, and their complements, the Turán graphs.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/algebraic-combinatorics] A Young tableau (pl.: *tableaux*) is a combinatorial object useful in representation theory and Schubert calculus.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/algebraic-combinatorics] It provides a convenient way to describe the group representations of the symmetric and general linear groups and to study their properties.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/algebraic-combinatorics] Young tableaux were introduced by Alfred Young, a mathematician at Cambridge University, in 1900.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/algebraic-combinatorics] They were then applied to the study of the symmetric group by Georg Frobenius in 1903.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/algebraic-combinatorics] Their theory was further developed by many mathematicians, including Percy MacMahon, W.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/algebraic-combinatorics] Robinson, Gian-Carlo Rota, Alain Lascoux, Marcel-Paul Schützenberger and Richard P.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/algebraic-combinatorics] A matroid is a structure that captures and generalizes the notion of linear independence in vector spaces.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/algebraic-combinatorics] There are many equivalent ways to define a matroid, the most significant being in terms of independent sets, bases, circuits, closed sets or flats, closure operators, and rank functions.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/algebraic-combinatorics] Matroid theory borrows extensively from the terminology of linear algebra and graph theory, largely because it is the abstraction of various notions of central importance in these fields.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/algebraic-combinatorics] Matroids have found applications in geometry, topology, combinatorial optimization, network theory and coding theory.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/algebraic-combinatorics] A finite geometry is any geometric system that has only a finite number of points.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/algebraic-combinatorics] The familiar Euclidean geometry is not finite, because a Euclidean line contains infinitely many points.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/algebraic-combinatorics] A geometry based on the graphics displayed on a computer screen, where the pixels are considered to be the points, would be a finite geometry.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/algebraic-combinatorics] While there are many systems that could be called finite geometries, attention is mostly paid to the finite projective and affine spaces because of their regularity and simplicity.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/algebraic-combinatorics] Other significant types of finite geometry are finite Möbius or inversive planes and Laguerre planes, which are examples of a general type called Benz planes, and their higher-dimensional analogs such as higher finite inversive geometries.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/algebraic-combinatorics] Finite geometries may be constructed via linear algebra, starting from vector spaces over a finite field; the affine and projective planes so constructed are called Galois geometries.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/algebraic-combinatorics] Finite geometries can also be defined purely axiomatically.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/algebraic-combinatorics] Most common finite geometries are Galois geometries, since any finite projective space of dimension three or greater is isomorphic to a projective space over a finite field (that is, the projectivization of a vector space over a finite field).
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/algebraic-combinatorics] However, dimension two has affine and projective planes that are not isomorphic to Galois geometries, namely the non-Desarguesian planes.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/algebraic-combinatorics] Similar results hold for other kinds of finite geometries.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/association-scheme] The theory of **association schemes** arose in statistics, in the theory of experimental design for the analysis of variance.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/association-scheme] In mathematics, association schemes belong to both algebra and combinatorics.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/association-scheme] In algebraic combinatorics, association schemes provide a unified approach to many topics, for example combinatorial designs and the theory of error-correcting codes.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/association-scheme] In algebra, the theory of association schemes generalizes the character theory of linear representations of groups.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/association-scheme] An association scheme is *commutative* if $p_{ij}^{k}=p_{ji}^{k}$ for all i , j and k .
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/association-scheme] Note, however, that while the notion of an association scheme generalizes the notion of a group, the notion of a commutative association scheme only generalizes the notion of a commutative group.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/association-scheme] A *symmetric* association scheme is one in which each $R_{i}$ is a symmetric relation.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/association-scheme] Every symmetric association scheme is commutative.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/association-scheme] Two points *x* and *y* are called *i*th associates if $(x,y)\in R_{i}$ .
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/association-scheme] The definition states that if *x* and *y* are *i*th associates then so are *y* and *x*.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/association-scheme] Every pair of points are *i*th associates for exactly one i .
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/association-scheme] Each point is its own zeroth associate while distinct points are never zeroth associates.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/association-scheme] If *x* and *y* are *k*th associates then the number of points z which are both *i*th associates of x and *j*th associates of y is a constant $p_{ij}^{k}$ .
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/association-scheme] A symmetric association scheme can be visualized as a complete graph with labeled edges.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/association-scheme] The graph has v vertices, one for each point of X , and the edge joining vertices x and y is labeled i if x and y are i th associates.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/association-scheme] Each edge has a unique label, and the number of triangles with a fixed base labeled k having the other edges labeled i and j is a constant $p_{ij}^{k}$ , depending on $i,j,k$ but not on the choice of the base.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/association-scheme] In particular, each vertex is incident with exactly $p_{ii}^{0}=v_{i}$ edges labeled i ; $v_{i}$ is the valency of the relation $R_{i}$ .
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/association-scheme] There are also loops labeled 0 at each vertex x , corresponding to $R_{0}$ .
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/association-scheme] The relations are described by their adjacency matrices. $A_{i}$ is the adjacency matrix of $R_{i}$ for $i=0,\ldots ,n$ and is a *v* × *v* matrix with rows and columns labeled by the points of X .
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/association-scheme] The (*x*, *y*)-th entry of the left side of (IV) is the number of paths of length two between *x* and *y* with labels *i* and *j* in the graph.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/association-scheme] The term *association scheme* is due to (Bose & Shimamoto 1952) but the concept is already inherent in (Bose & Nair 1939).
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/association-scheme] These authors were studying what statisticians have called *partially balanced incomplete block designs* (PBIBDs).
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/association-scheme] The subject became an object of algebraic interest with the publication of (Bose & Mesner 1959) and the introduction of the Bose–Mesner algebra.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/association-scheme] The most important contribution to the theory was the thesis of Ph.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/association-scheme] Delsarte (Delsarte 1973) who recognized and fully used the connections with coding theory and design theory.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/association-scheme] A generalization called coherent configurations has been studied by D.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/association-scheme] The adjacency matrices $A_{i}$ of the graphs $\left(X,R_{i}\right)$ generate a commutative and associative algebra ${\mathcal {A}}$ (over the real or complex numbers) both for the matrix product and the Hadamard (entrywise) product.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/association-scheme] The algebra formed with the matrix product is called the Bose–Mesner algebra of the association scheme.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/association-scheme] Since the matrices in ${\mathcal {A}}$ are symmetric and commute with each other, they can be diagonalized simultaneously.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/association-scheme] Therefore, ${\mathcal {A}}$ is semi-simple and has a unique basis of primitive idempotents $J_{0},\ldots ,J_{n}$ .
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/association-scheme] There is another algebra of $(n+1)\times (n+1)$ matrices which is isomorphic to ${\mathcal {A}}$ , and is often easier to work with.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/association-scheme] The Hamming scheme and the Johnson scheme are of major significance in classical coding theory.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/association-scheme] In coding theory, association scheme theory is mainly concerned with the distance of a code.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/association-scheme] The linear programming method produces upper bounds for the size of a code with given minimum distance, and lower bounds for the size of a design with a given strength.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/association-scheme] The most specific results are obtained in the case where the underlying association scheme satisfies certain polynomial properties; this leads one into the realm of orthogonal polynomials.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/association-scheme] In particular, some universal bounds are derived for codes and designs in polynomial-type association schemes.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/association-scheme] In classical coding theory, dealing with codes in a Hamming scheme, the MacWilliams transform involves a family of orthogonal polynomials known as the Krawtchouk polynomials.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/association-scheme] These polynomials give the eigenvalues of the distance relation matrices of the Hamming scheme.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] The **Möbius function $\mu (n)$** is a multiplicative function in number theory introduced by the German mathematician August Ferdinand Möbius (also transliterated *Moebius*) in 1832.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] It is ubiquitous in elementary and analytic number theory and most often appears as part of its namesake the Möbius inversion formula.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] Following work of Gian-Carlo Rota in the 1960s, generalizations of the Möbius function were introduced into combinatorics, and are similarly denoted $\mu (x)$ .
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] where $\delta _{ij}$ is the Kronecker delta, $\lambda (n)$ is the Liouville function, and $\omega (n)$ / $\Omega (n)$ are the Prime omega functions. $\omega (n)$ is the number of distinct prime divisors of n , and $\Omega (n)$ is the number of prime factors of n , counted with multiplicity.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] Another characterization by Carl Friedrich Gauss is the sum of all primitive roots.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] Gauss proved that for a prime number p the sum of its primitive roots is congruent to $\mu (p-1)\mod p$ .
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] The Möbius function is used in the Möbius inversion formula.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] The Möbius function also arises in the primon gas or free Riemann gas model of supersymmetry.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] In this theory, the fundamental particles or "primons" have energies $\log(p)$ .
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] Under second quantization, multiparticle excitations are considered; these are given by $\log(n)$ for any natural number n .
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] This follows from the fact that the factorization of the natural numbers into primes is unique.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] In the free Riemann gas, any natural number can occur, if the primons are taken as bosons.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] If they are taken as fermions, then the Pauli exclusion principle excludes squares.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] The operator $(-1)^{F}$ that distinguishes fermions and bosons is then none other than the Möbius function $\mu (n)$ .
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] The free Riemann gas has a number of other interesting connections to number theory, including the fact that the partition function is the Riemann zeta function.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] This idea underlies Alain Connes's attempted proof of the Riemann hypothesis.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] The Möbius function is multiplicative (i.e., $\mu (ab)=\mu (a)\mu (b)$ whenever a and b are coprime).
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] The equality above leads to the important Möbius inversion formula and is the main reason why $\mu$ is of relevance in the theory of multiplicative and arithmetic functions.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] Other applications of $\mu (n)$ in combinatorics are connected with the use of the Pólya enumeration theorem in combinatorial groups and combinatorial enumerations.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] i.e. $\mu (n)$ is the sum of the primitive n -th roots of unity.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] The first of these is a classical result while the second was published in 2020.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] Similar identities hold for the Mertens function.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] can be written using Dirichlet convolution as: $1*\mu =\varepsilon$ where $\varepsilon$ is the identity under the convolution.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] One way of proving this formula is by noting that the Dirichlet convolution of two multiplicative functions is again multiplicative.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] Thus it suffices to prove the formula for powers of primes.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] The formula above is then a consequence of the fact that the n th roots of unity sum to 0, since each n th root of unity is a primitive d th root of unity for exactly one divisor d of n .
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] However it is also possible to prove this identity from first principles.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] First note that it is trivially true when $n=1$ .
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] Then there is a bijection between the factors d of n for which $\mu (d)\neq 0$ and the subsets of the set of all prime factors of n .
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] The asserted result follows from the fact that every non-empty finite set has an equal number of odd- and even-cardinality subsets.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] This last fact can be shown easily by induction on the cardinality $|S|$ of a non-empty finite set S .
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] First, if $|S|=1$ , there is exactly one odd-cardinality subset of S , namely S itself, and exactly one even-cardinality subset, namely $\emptyset$ .
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] Next, if $|S|>1$ , then divide the subsets of S into two subclasses depending on whether they contain or not some fixed element x in S .
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] There is an obvious bijection between these two subclasses, pairing those subsets that have the same complement relative to the subset $\{x\}$ .
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] Also, one of these two subclasses consists of all the subsets of the set $S\setminus \{x\}$ , and therefore, by the induction hypothesis, has an equal number of odd- and even-cardinality subsets.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] These subsets in turn correspond bijectively to the even- and odd-cardinality $\{x\}$ -containing subsets of S .
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] The inductive step follows directly from these two bijections.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] A related result is that the binomial coefficients exhibit alternating entries of odd and even power which sum symmetrically.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] The mean value (in the sense of average orders) of the Möbius function is zero.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] This statement is, in fact, equivalent to the prime number theorem.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] $\mu (n)=0$ if and only if n is divisible by the square of a prime.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] If n is prime, then $\mu (n)=-1$ , but the converse is not true.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] The first non prime n for which $\mu (n)=-1$ is $30=2\times 3\times 5$ .
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] This function is closely linked with the positions of zeroes of the Riemann zeta function.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] See the article on the Mertens conjecture for more information about the connection between $M(n)$ and the Riemann hypothesis.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] where ${\mathcal {F}}_{n}$ is the Farey sequence of order n .
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] This formula is used in the proof of the Franel–Landau theorem.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] In combinatorics, every locally finite partially ordered set (poset) is assigned an incidence algebra.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] One distinguished member of this algebra is that poset's "Möbius function".
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] The classical Möbius function treated in this article is essentially equal to the Möbius function of the set of all positive integers partially ordered by divisibility.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] See the article on incidence algebras for the precise definition and several examples of these general Möbius functions.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] Because the Möbius function is multipliciative, so is its (iterated) Dirichlet convolution $\mu _{k}=\mu *\cdots *\mu$ to be the k -fold Dirichlet convolution of the Möbius function with itself.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] We then have $\mu _{k}\left(p^{a}\right)=(-1)^{a}{\binom {k}{a}}$ where the binomial coefficient is taken to be zero if $a>k$ .
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/möbius-function] The definition may be extended to complex k by reading the binomial as a polynomial in k .
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] In mathematics, especially order theory, a **partial order** on a set is an arrangement such that, for certain pairs of elements, one precedes the other.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] The word *partial* is used to indicate that not every pair of elements needs to be comparable; that is, there may be pairs for which neither element precedes the other.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] Partial orders thus generalize total orders, in which every pair is comparable.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] Formally, a partial order is a homogeneous binary relation that is reflexive, antisymmetric, and transitive.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] A **partially ordered set** (**poset** for short) is an ordered pair $P=(X,\leq )$ consisting of a set X (called the *ground set* of P ) and a partial order $\leq$ on X .
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] When the meaning is clear from context and there is no ambiguity about the partial order, the set X itself is sometimes called a poset.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] The term *partial order* usually refers to the reflexive partial order relations, referred to in this article as *non-strict* partial orders.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] However some authors use the term for the other common type of partial order relations, the irreflexive partial order relations, also called strict partial orders.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] Strict and non-strict partial orders can be put into a one-to-one correspondence, so for every strict partial order there is a unique corresponding non-strict partial order, and vice versa.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] A **reflexive**, **weak**, or **non-strict partial order**, commonly referred to simply as a **partial order**, is a homogeneous relation ≤ on a set P that is reflexive, antisymmetric, and transitive.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] Antisymmetry: if $a\leq b$ and $b\leq a$ then $a=b$ , i.e. no two distinct elements precede each other.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] Transitivity: if $a\leq b$ and $b\leq c$ then $a\leq c$ .
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] A non-strict partial order is also known as an antisymmetric preorder.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] Transitivity: if $a<b$ and $b<c$ then $a<c$ .
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] A transitive relation is asymmetric if and only if it is irreflexive.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] So the definition is the same if it omits either irreflexivity or asymmetry (but not both).
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] A strict partial order is also known as a strict preorder.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] Strict and non-strict partial orders on a set P are closely related.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] Conversely, a strict partial order < on P may be converted to a non-strict partial order by adjoining all relationships of that form; that is, $\leq \;:=\;\Delta _{P}\;\cup \;<\;$ is a non-strict partial order.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] The *dual* (or *opposite*) $R^{\text{op}}$ of a partial order relation R is defined by letting $R^{\text{op}}$ be the converse relation of R , i.e. $xR^{\text{op}}y$ if and only if $yRx$ .
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] The dual of a non-strict partial order is a non-strict partial order, and the dual of a strict partial order is a strict partial order.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] The dual of a dual of a relation is the original relation.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] Strictly speaking, the term *partially ordered set* refers to a set with all of these relations defined appropriately.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] But practically, one need only consider a single relation, $(P,\leq )$ or $(P,<)$ , or, in rare instances, the non-strict and strict relations together, $(P,\leq ,<)$ .
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] The term *ordered set* is sometimes used as a shorthand for *partially ordered set*, as long as it is clear from the context that no other kind of order is meant.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] In particular, totally ordered sets can also be referred to as "ordered sets", especially in areas where these structures are more common than posets.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] Some authors use different symbols than $\leq$ such as $\sqsubseteq$ or $\preceq$ to distinguish partial orders from total orders.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] When referring to partial orders, $\leq$ should not be taken as the complement of > .
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] The relation > is the converse of the irreflexive kernel of $\leq$ , which is always a subset of the complement of $\leq$ , but > is equal to the complement of $\leq$ if, and only if, $\leq$ is a total order.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] Another way of defining a partial order, found in computer science, is via a notion of comparison.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] Specifically, given $\leq ,<,\geq ,{\text{ and }}>$ as defined previously, it can be observed that two elements *x* and *y* may stand in any of four mutually exclusive relationships to each other: either *x* < *y*, or *x* = *y*, or *x* > *y*, or *x* and *y* are *incomparable*.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] This can be represented by a function ${\text{compare}}:P\times P\to \{<,>,=,\vert \}$ that returns one of four codes when given two elements.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] This definition is equivalent to a *partial order on a setoid*, where equality is taken to be a defined equivalence relation rather than set equality.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] Wallis defines a more general notion of a *partial order relation* as any homogeneous relation that is transitive and antisymmetric.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] This includes both reflexive and irreflexive partial orders as subtypes.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] A finite poset can be visualized through its Hasse diagram.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] Specifically, taking a strict partial order relation $(P,<)$ , a directed acyclic graph (DAG) may be constructed by taking each element of P to be a node and each element of < to be an edge.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] The transitive reduction of this DAG is then the Hasse diagram.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] Similarly this process can be reversed to construct strict partial orders from certain DAGs.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] In contrast, the graph associated to a non-strict partial order has self-loops at every node and therefore is not a DAG; when a non-strict order is said to be depicted by a Hasse diagram, actually the corresponding strict order is shown.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] One familiar example of a partially ordered set is a collection of people ordered by genealogical descendancy.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] Some pairs of people bear the descendant-ancestor relationship, but other pairs of people are incomparable, with neither being a descendant of the other.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] are highlighted in green and red, respectively.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] In order of increasing strength, i.e., decreasing sets of pairs, three of the possible partial orders on the Cartesian product of two partially ordered sets are (see Fig.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] All three can similarly be defined for the Cartesian product of more than two sets.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] Applied to ordered vector spaces over the same field, the result is in each case also an ordered vector space.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] See also orders on the Cartesian product of totally ordered sets.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] If two posets are well-ordered, then so is their ordinal sum.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] Series-parallel partial orders are formed from the ordinal sum operation (in this context called series composition) and another operation called parallel composition.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] Parallel composition is the disjoint union of two partially ordered sets, with no order relation between elements of one set and elements of the other set.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] The examples use the poset $({\mathcal {P}}(\{x,y,z\}),\subseteq )$ consisting of the set of all subsets of a three-element set $\{x,y,z\},$ ordered by set inclusion (see Fig.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] As another example, consider the positive integers, ordered by divisibility: 1 is a least element, as it divides all other elements; on the other hand this poset does not have a greatest element.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] This partially ordered set does not even have any maximal elements, since any *g* divides for instance 2*g*, which is distinct from it, so *g* is not maximal.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] If the number 1 is excluded, while keeping divisibility as ordering on the elements greater than 1, then the resulting poset does not have a least element, but any prime number is a minimal element for it.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] In this poset, 60 is an upper bound (though not a least upper bound) of the subset $\{2,3,5,10\},$ which does not have any lower bound (since 1 is not in the poset); on the other hand 2 is a lower bound of the subset of powers of 2, which does not have any upper bound.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] If the number 0 is included, this will be the greatest element, since this is a multiple of every integer (see Fig.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] Given two partially ordered sets (*S*, ≤) and (*T*, ≼), a function $f:S\to T$ is called **order-preserving**, or **monotone**, or **isotone**, if for all $x,y\in S,$ $x\leq y$ implies *f*(*x*) ≼ *f*(*y*).
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] If (*U*, ≲) is also a partially ordered set, and both $f:S\to T$ and $g:T\to U$ are order-preserving, their composition $g\circ f:S\to U$ is order-preserving, too.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] A function $f:S\to T$ is called **order-reflecting** if for all $x,y\in S,$ *f*(*x*) ≼ *f*(*y*) implies $x\leq y.$ If f is both order-preserving and order-reflecting, then it is called an **order-embedding** of (*S*, ≤) into (*T*, ≼).
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] In the latter case, f is necessarily injective, since $f(x)=f(y)$ implies $x\leq y{\text{ and }}y\leq x$ and in turn $x=y$ according to the antisymmetry of $\leq .$ If an order-embedding between two posets *S* and *T* exists, one says that *S* can be **embedded** into *T*.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] If an order-embedding $f:S\to T$ is bijective, it is called an **order isomorphism**, and the partial orders (*S*, ≤) and (*T*, ≼) are said to be **isomorphic**.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] Isomorphic orders have structurally similar Hasse diagrams (see Fig.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] It can be shown that if order-preserving maps $f:S\to T$ and $g:T\to U$ exist such that $g\circ f$ and $f\circ g$ yields the identity function on *S* and *T*, respectively, then *S* and *T* are order-isomorphic.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] For example, a mapping $f:\mathbb {N} \to \mathbb {P} (\mathbb {N} )$ from the set of natural numbers (ordered by divisibility) to the power set of natural numbers (ordered by set inclusion) can be defined by taking each number to the set of its prime divisors.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] It is order-preserving: if x divides y, then each prime divisor of x is also a prime divisor of y.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] However, it is neither injective (since it maps both 12 and 6 to $\{2,3\}$ ) nor order-reflecting (since 12 does not divide 6).
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] Taking instead each number to the set of its prime power divisors defines a map $g:\mathbb {N} \to \mathbb {P} (\mathbb {N} )$ that is order-preserving, order-reflecting, and hence an order-embedding.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] It is not an order-isomorphism (since it, for instance, does not map any number to the set $\{4\}$ ), but it can be made one by restricting its codomain to $g(\mathbb {N} ).$ Fig.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] 7b shows a subset of $\mathbb {N}$ and its isomorphic image under g.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] The construction of such an order-isomorphism into a power set can be generalized to a wide class of partial orders, called distributive lattices; see *Birkhoff's representation theorem*.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] Note that *S*(*n*, *k*) refers to Stirling numbers of the second kind.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] The number of strict partial orders is the same as that of partial orders.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] If the count is made only up to isomorphism, the sequence 1, 1, 2, 5, 16, 63, 318, ...
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] (sequence A000112 in the OEIS) is obtained.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] A poset $P^{*}=(X^{*},\leq ^{*})$ is called a **subposet** of another poset $P=(X,\leq )$ provided that $X^{*}$ is a subset of X and $\leq ^{*}$ is a subset of $\leq$ .
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] The latter condition is equivalent to the requirement that for any x and y in $X^{*}$ (and thus also in X ), if $x\leq ^{*}y$ then $x\leq y$ .
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] If $P^{*}$ is a subposet of P and furthermore, for all x and y in $X^{*}$ , whenever $x\leq y$ we also have $x\leq ^{*}y$ , then we call $P^{*}$ the subposet of P **induced** by $X^{*}$ , and write $P^{*}=P[X^{*}]$ .
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] A partial order $\leq ^{*}$ on a set X is called an **extension** of another partial order $\leq$ on X provided that for all elements $x,y\in X,$ whenever $x\leq y,$ it is also the case that $x\leq ^{*}y.$ A linear extension is an extension that is also a linear (that is, total) order.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] As a classic example, the lexicographic order of totally ordered sets is a linear extension of their product order.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] Every partial order can be extended to a total order (order-extension principle).
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] In computer science, algorithms for finding linear extensions of partial orders (represented as the reachability orders of directed acyclic graphs) are called topological sorting.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] Posets are equivalent to one another if and only if they are isomorphic.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] In a poset, the smallest element, if it exists, is an initial object, and the largest element, if it exists, is a terminal object.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] Also, every preordered set is equivalent to a poset.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] Finally, every subcategory of a poset is isomorphism-closed.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] A **convex set** in a poset *P* is a subset I of *P* with the property that, for any *x* and *y* in I and any *z* in *P*, if *x* ≤ *z* ≤ *y*, then *z* is also in I.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] This definition generalizes the definition of intervals of real numbers.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] When there is possible confusion with convex sets of geometry, one uses **order-convex** instead of "convex".
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] A **convex sublattice** of a lattice *L* is a sublattice of *L* that is also a convex set of *L*.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] Every nonempty convex sublattice can be uniquely represented as the intersection of a filter and an ideal of *L*.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] Whenever *a* ≤ *b* does not hold, all these intervals are empty.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] Every interval is a convex set, but the converse does not hold; for example, in the poset of divisors of 120, ordered by divisibility (see Fig.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] 7b), the set {1, 2, 4, 5, 8} is convex, but not an interval.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] An interval I is bounded if there exist elements $a,b\in P$ such that *I* ⊆ [*a*, *b*].
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] Every interval that can be represented in interval notation is obviously bounded, but the converse is not true.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] For example, let *P* = (0, 1) ∪ (1, 2) ∪ (2, 3) as a subposet of the real numbers.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] The subset (1, 2) is a bounded interval, but it has no infimum or supremum in *P*, so it cannot be written in interval notation using elements of *P*.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] A poset is called locally finite if every bounded interval is finite.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] For example, the integers are locally finite under their natural ordering.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] The lexicographical order on the cartesian product $\mathbb {N} \times \mathbb {N}$ is not locally finite, since (1, 2) ≤ (1, 3) ≤ (1, 4) ≤ (1, 5) ≤ ... ≤ (2, 1).
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/partially-ordered-set] This concept of an interval in a partial order should not be confused with the particular class of partial orders known as the interval orders.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/symmetric-function] In mathematics, a function of n variables is **symmetric** if its value is the same no matter the order of its arguments.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/symmetric-function] A related notion is alternating polynomials, which change sign under an interchange of variables.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/symmetric-function] Given any function f in n variables with values in an abelian group, a symmetric function can be constructed by summing values of f over all permutations of the arguments.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/symmetric-function] Similarly, an anti-symmetric function can be constructed by summing over even permutations and subtracting the sum over odd permutations.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/symmetric-function] In statistics, an n -sample statistic (a function in n variables) that is obtained by bootstrapping symmetrization of a k -sample statistic, yielding a symmetric function in n variables, is called a U-statistic.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/symmetric-function] Examples include the sample mean and sample variance.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] In mathematics, a **Young tableau** (/tæˈbloʊ, ˈtæbloʊ/; plural: **tableaux**) is a combinatorial object useful in representation theory and Schubert calculus.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] A **Young diagram** (also called a Ferrers diagram, particularly when represented using dots) is a finite collection of boxes, or cells, arranged in left-justified rows, with the row lengths in non-increasing order.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] Listing the number of boxes in each row gives a partition λ of a non-negative integer n, the total number of boxes of the diagram.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] The Young diagram is said to be of shape λ, and it carries the same information as that partition.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] Containment of one Young diagram in another defines a partial ordering on the set of all partitions, which is in fact a lattice structure, known as Young's lattice.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] Listing the number of boxes of a Young diagram in each column gives another partition, the *conjugate* or *transpose* partition of λ; one obtains a Young diagram of that shape by reflecting the original diagram along its main diagonal.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] There is almost universal agreement that in labeling boxes of Young diagrams by pairs of integers, the first index selects the row of the diagram, and the second index selects the box within the row.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] Nevertheless, two distinct conventions exist to display these diagrams, and consequently tableaux: the first places each row below the previous one, the second stacks each row on top of the previous one.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] This nomenclature probably started out as jocular.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] The English notation corresponds to the one universally used for matrices, while the French notation is closer to the convention of Cartesian coordinates; however, French notation differs from that convention by placing the vertical coordinate first.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] The figure on the right shows, using the English notation, the Young diagram corresponding to the partition (5, 4, 1) of the number 10.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] The conjugate partition, measuring the column lengths, is (3, 2, 2, 2, 1).
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] In many applications, for example when defining Jack functions, it is convenient to define the *arm length* *a*λ(*s*) of a box *s* as the number of boxes to the right of *s* in the diagram λ in English notation.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] Similarly, the *leg length* *l*λ(*s*) is the number of boxes below *s*.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] The *hook length* of a box *s* is the number of boxes to the right of *s* or below *s* in English notation, including the box *s* itself; in other words, the hook length is *a*λ(*s*) + *l*λ(*s*) + 1.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] A **Young tableau** is obtained by filling in the boxes of the Young diagram with symbols taken from some *alphabet*, which is usually required to be a totally ordered set.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] Originally that alphabet was a set of indexed variables *x*1, *x*2, *x*3, ..., but now one usually uses a set of numbers for brevity.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] In their original application to representations of the symmetric group, Young tableaux have n distinct entries, arbitrarily assigned to boxes of the diagram.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] A tableau is called *standard* if the entries in each row and each column are increasing.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] In other applications, it is natural to allow the same number to appear more than once (or not at all) in a tableau.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] A tableau is called *semistandard*, or *column strict*, if the entries weakly increase along each row and strictly increase down each column.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] Recording the number of times each number appears in a tableau gives a sequence known as the *weight* of the tableau.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] Thus the standard Young tableaux are precisely the semistandard tableaux of weight (1, 1, ..., 1), which requires every integer up to n to occur exactly once.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] In a standard Young tableau, the integer k is a *descent* if $k+1$ appears in a row strictly below k .
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] The sum of the descents is called the *major index* of the tableau.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] There are several variations of this definition: for example, in a row-strict tableau the entries strictly increase along the rows and weakly increase down the columns.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] Also, tableaux with *decreasing* entries have been considered, notably, in the theory of plane partitions.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] There are also generalizations such as domino tableaux or ribbon tableaux, in which several boxes may be grouped together before assigning entries to them.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] A *skew shape* is a pair of partitions (*λ*, *μ*) such that the Young diagram of *λ* contains the Young diagram of *μ*; it is denoted by *λ*/*μ*.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] The *skew diagram* of a skew shape *λ*/*μ* is the set-theoretic difference of the Young diagrams of *λ* and *μ*: the set of squares that belong to the diagram of *λ* but not to that of *μ*.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] While the map from partitions to their Young diagrams is injective, this is not the case for the map from skew shapes to skew diagrams; therefore the shape of a skew diagram cannot always be determined from the set of filled squares only.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] Young tableaux can be identified with skew tableaux in which *μ* is the empty partition (0) (the unique partition of 0).
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] Any pair of successive shapes in such a sequence is a skew shape whose diagram contains at most one box in each column; such shapes are called *horizontal strips*.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] This sequence of partitions completely determines *T*, and it is in fact possible to define (skew) semistandard tableaux as such sequences, as is done by Macdonald (Macdonald 1979, p.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] This definition incorporates the partitions *λ* and *μ* in the data comprising the skew tableau.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] Young tableaux have numerous applications in combinatorics, representation theory, and algebraic geometry.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] Various ways of counting Young tableaux have been explored and lead to the definition of and identities for Schur functions.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] Many combinatorial algorithms on tableaux are known, including Schützenberger's jeu de taquin and the Robinson–Schensted–Knuth correspondence.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] Lascoux and Schützenberger studied an associative product on the set of all semistandard Young tableaux, giving it the structure called the *plactic monoid* (French: *le monoïde plaxique*).
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] In representation theory, standard Young tableaux of size *k* describe bases in irreducible representations of the symmetric group on *k* letters.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] The standard monomial basis in a finite-dimensional irreducible representation of the general linear group *GL**n* are parametrized by the set of semistandard Young tableaux of a fixed shape over the alphabet {1, 2, ..., *n*}.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] This has important consequences for invariant theory, starting from the work of Hodge on the homogeneous coordinate ring of the Grassmannian and further explored by Gian-Carlo Rota with collaborators, de Concini and Procesi, and Eisenbud.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] The Littlewood–Richardson rule describing (among other things) the decomposition of tensor products of irreducible representations of *GL**n* into irreducible components is formulated in terms of certain skew semistandard tableaux.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] Applications to algebraic geometry center around Schubert calculus on Grassmannians and flag varieties.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] Certain important cohomology classes can be represented by Schubert polynomials and described in terms of Young tableaux.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] Young diagrams are in one-to-one correspondence with irreducible representations of the symmetric group over the complex numbers.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] They provide a convenient way of specifying the Young symmetrizers from which the irreducible representations are built.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] Many facts about a representation can be deduced from the corresponding diagram.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] Below, we describe two examples: determining the dimension of a representation and restricted representations.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] In both cases, we will see that some properties of a representation can be determined by using just its diagram.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] Young tableaux are involved in the use of the symmetric group in quantum chemistry studies of atoms, molecules and solids.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] In these cases semistandard tableaux with entries up to *n* play a central role, rather than standard tableaux; in particular it is the number of those tableaux that determines the dimension of the representation.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] The dimension of the irreducible representation π*λ* of the symmetric group *S**n* corresponding to a partition *λ* of *n* is equal to the number of different standard Young tableaux that can be obtained from the diagram of the representation.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] This number can be calculated by the hook length formula.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] A *hook length* hook(*x*) of a box *x* in Young diagram *Y*(*λ*) of shape *λ* is the number of boxes that are in the same row to the right of it plus those boxes in the same column below it, plus one (for the box itself).
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] The figure on the right shows hook-lengths for all boxes in the diagram of the partition 10 = 5 + 4 + 1.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] where the index *i* gives the row and *j* the column of a box.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] A representation of the symmetric group on *n* elements, *S**n* is also a representation of the symmetric group on *n* − 1 elements, *S**n*−1.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] However, an irreducible representation of *S**n* may not be irreducible for *S**n*−1.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] Instead, it may be a direct sum of several representations that are irreducible for *S**n*−1.
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] These representations are then called the factors of the restricted representation (see also induced representation).
[src:algebraic-combinatorics/young-tableau] The question of determining this decomposition of the restricted representation of a given irreducible representation of *S**n*, corresponding to a partition *λ* of *n*, is answered as follows.
